<DocsLayout
  title="Heavy compute fan-out"
  description="Use remote_parallel_map inside a Python model for massive per-row parallelism."
  lede="The pattern for CPU-heavy per-row work — a Monte-Carlo estimate of pi stands in for any per-row numerical computation. Each row goes to a Burla worker; with burla_fake: true it runs in-process so you can try it without a cluster."
  prev={{ title: "BigQuery LLM enrichment", href: withBase("/examples/bigquery-llm-enrichment/") }}
  next={{ title: "All examples", href: withBase("/examples/") }}
>
  <h2>Run it</h2>
  <Code code={`cd dbt-burla/examples/04-fan-out-heavy-compute
pip install "dbt-burla[duckdb]"
dbt run --profiles-dir .`} lang="bash" theme="github-dark-dimmed" />

  <p>You'll see one SQL model (<code>stg_inputs</code>) and one Python model (<code>computed_features</code>). The Python model runs <code>_monte_carlo_pi</code> on every row, with each row shipped to a Burla worker in fake mode.</p>

  <h2>The model</h2>
  <Code code={`# models/computed_features.py
import random

import pandas as pd
from burla import remote_parallel_map


def _monte_carlo_pi(row: dict) -> dict:
    """Per-worker CPU-heavy computation."""
    n = int(row["n_samples"])
    rng = random.Random(row["id"])
    inside = 0
    for _ in range(n):
        x, y = rng.random(), rng.random()
        if x * x + y * y <= 1.0:
            inside += 1
    return {**row, "pi_estimate": 4.0 * inside / max(n, 1), "error": None}


def model(dbt, session):
    dbt.config(
        materialized="table",
        burla_workers=1000,       # 1000 workers
        burla_cpus_per_worker=4,
    )

    inputs = dbt.ref("stg_inputs").to_dict("records")
    results = list(remote_parallel_map(_monte_carlo_pi, inputs))
    return pd.DataFrame(results)`} lang="python" theme="github-dark-dimmed" />

  <h2>When to use this pattern</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>Per-row ML inference</li>
    <li>Per-row API calls (translation, enrichment, scraping)</li>
    <li>Heavy numerical work (simulation, optimization, image/audio)</li>
    <li>Any workload where the per-row function takes more than a few ms</li>
  </ul>

  <p>For very short per-row work (&lt;1ms), batch rows before submitting — ship a chunk of 100 or 1000 rows at a time to each worker:</p>

  <Code code={`def _process_batch(batch: list[dict]) -> list[dict]:
    return [_monte_carlo_pi(row) for row in batch]


def model(dbt, session):
    dbt.config(materialized="table", burla_workers=100)
    rows = dbt.ref("stg_inputs").to_dict("records")
    batches = [rows[i:i + 100] for i in range(0, len(rows), 100)]
    results = [row for batch in remote_parallel_map(_process_batch, batches) for row in batch]
    return pd.DataFrame(results)`} lang="python" theme="github-dark-dimmed" />
</DocsLayout>
